AB  - This paper considers a two-country-two-good model of international trade where in each country employment and output are constrained by effective demand. It is shown that the country (identified as the South) exporting consumption goods and importing investment goods in trade equilibrium experiences an unambiguous fall in consumption and employment as trade opens up. The other country (identified as the North) experiences an unambiguous rise in consumption and employment.
