DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(89)90052-7
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387889900527
AB  - The effect of export expansion on economic growth is examined through an intercountry aggregate analysis of the sources of growth. The hypothesis that the relationship under consideration is significantly affected by the level of development is tested within a switching regression framework. The results indicate the existence of a critical development level below and above which the responses of output growth to its determining factors differ substantially. The evidence contradicts the view that among ‘more advanced’ developing economies the effect of export expansion on growth is stronger than among ‘less advanced’ ones.
